Yingyue Ding, Kevin Huang, Sunyimeng Lei, Clarissa Halim

11/18/2019

https://github.com/dyy980617/Bio201ThursPM/tree/master/Bio201ThursPM

Research Question: How does the consumption of a prebiotic effect the gut microbiomal community(diversity, changes in taxon abundance) among people who have different fiber diet?

Since we got significant difference from BRMPS consumption in the BRMPS Rmd, In this Rmd we will be testing how a fixed routine of low fiber daily with the consumption of BRMPS will effect once gut microbiomal commnity in regard of richness and simpson diversity index, and beta divesity.We selceted for quantity compliant. Our hypothesis is there gonna be significant difference in these index.

Import data

Sequence variants

Import shared/ESV/OTU table and format for phyloseq. Phyloseq works by matching rownames across matrix objects (This is similar to how we matched columns in joins of data frames). A two-dimensional matrix in R looks just like a data frame, however R matrices can be three-dimensional. A three-dimensional object is created when multiple two-dimensional objects are combined (well work through this in the upcoming sections).

Create phyloseq objects

Phyloseq is an R package that has a suite of functions that make microbial community anaylsis a bit simpler. https://joey711.github.io/phyloseq/index.html It requires the data to be structured in three critical files (1) sequence variant (or OTU) table that contains counts of each sequence; (2) Taxanomic information that contains classifications from Phylum to species for each sequence variant; (3) sample information, which is the participant information we have been working with so far this semester. We imported these three files in the section above, now we have to combine them into one object.

physq_obj <- phyloseq(sv_table, taxa, all_data_wkly_inner) #combine three phyloseq objects created above 

physq_obj #view dimentions of new object 
## phyloseq-class experiment-level object
## otu_table()   OTU Table:         [ 1160 taxa and 1148 samples ]
## sample_data() Sample Data:       [ 1148 samples by 18 sample variables ]
## tax_table()   Taxonomy Table:    [ 1160 taxa by 1 taxonomic ranks ]

Richness

There are numerous alpha diversity metrics, however we are going to focus on number richness, evenness, and Simpson for our analyses. We will calculate, plot, extract information about alpha diversity with the plot_richness() funciton.

Calculate richness

# Caculate richness

richness_df_fib <- physq_obj %>%
  subset_samples(quantity_compliant == "yes") %>%
  subset_samples(., study_week == "week1" | study_week == "week3") %>% 
   subset_samples(supplement_consumed == "BRMPS")%>%
  subset_samples(., fiber_status == "low") %>% #subset for weeks of interest
 # subset_taxa(Species == starts_with("Bifidobacterium"))
  estimate_richness(., split = TRUE,  measures = c("Observed")) %>% #calculate richness
  rownames_to_column(var = "participant_id_week") %>% #reverse phyloseq object formatting
  inner_join(all_data_wkly_fib, by = "participant_id_week")%>%
select(participant_id, study_week, Observed)%>%
  rename(richness_fib = Observed) 
 

# save richness data 
write_delim(richness_df_fib, path = "~/Documents/Bio201ThursPM/curated_data/richness_df_fib_low.txt", delim = "\t")

p-value = 0.1024, no signicant difference in richness when consuming BRMPS when fiber status is fixed to a low level.

Simpson

To calculate Simpson diveristy index we repeat the process above for calcuating richness, the only thing we have to change is the measures = c("Simpson") argument for the plot_richness() and estimate_richness() functions.

Calculate simpson

simpson_df_fib <- physq_obj %>%
  subset_samples(quantity_compliant == "yes") %>%
  subset_samples(supplement_consumed == "BRMPS")%>%
  subset_samples(., fiber_status == "low") %>% 
  subset_samples(., study_week == "week1" | study_week == "week3") %>% #subset for weeks of interest
  estimate_richness(., split = TRUE,  measures = c("Simpson")) %>% #calculate simpson
  rownames_to_column(var = "participant_id_week") %>% #reverse phyloseq object formatting
  inner_join(all_data_wkly_fib, by = "participant_id_week")%>%
select(participant_id, study_week, Simpson)%>%
  rename(simpson_fib = Simpson) 

# save Simpson data 
write_delim(simpson_df_fib, path = "~/Documents/Bio201ThursPM/curated_data/simpson_df_fib_low.txt", delim = "\t")

Beta diveristy

Conduct ordination analysis

This step calculates the diveristy index (using Bray Curtis in the example below), and does the ranking process of the diveristy indices to generate the information necessary to create a two-dimensional plot. Notice the arguments in the ordinate function; the index, Bray Curtis (bray) or Jaccard (jaccard), is specified in the distance agurment, and with either of these metrics we will use method = NMDS. The place were you might want to make some modifications is the k (this should be somewhere between 1-3), the maximum number of iterations (more than 100 will take several minutes to calcaulte), and the inital number of interations to try (50 in the example below). These can be modified to reduce the stress, with the goal of a number less than 0.20 (the lower the better).

# Bray Curtis
physq_sub <- physq_obj %>%
 subset_samples(quantity_compliant == "yes") %>%
  
  subset_samples(supplement_consumed == "BRMPS")%>%
subset_samples(study_week == "week1" | study_week == "week3") %>% 
  subset_samples( fiber_status == "low")
physq_sub
## phyloseq-class experiment-level object
## otu_table()   OTU Table:         [ 1160 taxa and 208 samples ]
## sample_data() Sample Data:       [ 208 samples by 18 sample variables ]
## tax_table()   Taxonomy Table:    [ 1160 taxa by 1 taxonomic ranks ]
physq_bc <- ordinate(physq_sub, 
                      method = "NMDS", 
                      k=3, maxit=100, try=50,
                      distance = "bray")

Statistical test

# run Bray Curtis test
dat_bray <- phyloseq::distance(physq_sub, method = "bray") 

sampledf <- physq_sub %>% 
  sample_data(.) %>% 
  as(., "data.frame") 


adn_res <- adonis(formula = dat_bray ~ study_week, 
                  data = sampledf)



print(adn_res)
## 
## Call:
## adonis(formula = dat_bray ~ study_week, data = sampledf) 
## 
## Permutation: free
## Number of permutations: 999
## 
## Terms added sequentially (first to last)
## 
##             Df SumsOfSqs MeanSqs F.Model      R2 Pr(>F)   
## study_week   1     0.595 0.59546  2.6774 0.01283  0.007 **
## Residuals  206    45.814 0.22240         0.98717          
## Total      207    46.409                 1.00000          
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

p-value of 0.002 indicates the groups are statistically significant. The R-squared value can be interpretd as the effect size, it shows the percentage of variation explained by the grouping categories.an R value of 0.013 here indicates no significant dissimilarity between the groups, that the grouping of samples based by study week are weak. When this occurs (low p and low R), the variation of the samples in the tested groups likely is influencing the results of the test.

# run Jaccard test
dat_ja <- phyloseq::distance(physq_sub, method = "jaccard") 

sampledf <- physq_sub %>% 
  sample_data(.) %>% 
  as(., "data.frame")

                  data = sampledf)
